---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';

const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "datePublished": "2026-07-13",
  "dateModified": "2026-07-13",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Why do I need a UPS for my gaming PC?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "A Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS) protects your components from power surges, brownouts, and blackouts. It provides instant battery power to allow you to save your work and shut down your PC safely, avoiding data corruption."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How do I size a UPS for my PC?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "You must choose a UPS with a wattage output rating higher than your PC's maximum load draw under gaming stress. A typical 850W PC needs a UPS rated for at least 1500VA / 900W."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---

<Layout
  title="UPS & Surge Protectors: Sizing Battery Backups — PSUCheck"
  description="Learn how to choose and size a Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS) for your custom gaming desktop. Explains VA ratings, sine wave types, and safety."
  schema={faqSchema}
>
  <article class="guide-article">
    <div class="container">
      <header class="guide-header">
        <div class="guide-meta">
          <span class="badge badge-safe">✓ E-E-A-T Verified</span>
          <span>Updated: July 13, 2026</span>
        </div>
        <h1>UPS &amp; Surge Protection Sizing Guide</h1>
        <p class="guide-lead">
          Blackouts and brownouts can ruin expensive PC hardware.
          This guide outlines how to choose the right battery backup (UPS) for your desktop.
        </p>
      </header>

      <div class="guide-layout">
        <main class="guide-content" id="main-content">
          <h2>Surge Protector vs. UPS</h2>
          <p>
            A standard surge protector strip redirects voltage spikes (such as lightning strikes) to the ground.
            A Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS) does this as well, but also includes a large internal battery
            that kicks in within 4-12 milliseconds when power drops.
          </p>

          <h2>VA vs. Wattage Ratings</h2>
          <p>
            UPS systems are rated in Volt-Amps (VA) and Watts. The Wattage rating is the critical number.
            If your gaming PC draws 650W under load and you hook it to a UPS rated for 1000VA / 600W,
            the UPS will trip its overload circuit and turn off the moment you start gaming.
          </p>
          <div class="important-warning">
            <strong>⚠ Pure Sine Wave Rule:</strong> Modern high-end PSUs with Active PFC (Power Factor Correction)
            require a <strong>Pure Sine Wave</strong> UPS. Cheap "Simulated" or "Modified" sine wave backups can cause
            Active PFC power supplies to buzz, drop efficiency, or shut down entirely.
          </div>

          <h2>How much battery runtime do you get?</h2>
          <p>
            A standard 1500VA UPS will keep a 400W gaming system running for roughly 5 to 10 minutes.
            This is not designed for continuous gaming, but rather to give you enough time to save files,
            close games, and execute a graceful OS shutdown.
          </p>

          <div style="margin-top:3rem;">
            <a href="/psu-calculator" class="btn btn-primary">Check load requirements</a>
          </div>
        </main>

        <aside class="guide-sidebar">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Calculators</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/psu-calculator">⚡ PSU Calculator</a></li>
              <li><a href="/pc-builder">🖥️ PC Build Cost Calculator</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Other Guides</h3>
            <ul style="list-style:none;padding:0;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:0.5rem;font-size:0.875rem;">
              <li><a href="/guides/psu-efficiency-guide">80+ Efficiency Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/psu-sizing-guide">PSU Sizing Guide</a></li>
              <li><a href="/guides/atx-3-1-guide">ATX 3.1 Guide</a></li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
.guide-article { padding: 4rem 0; }
.guide-header { margin-bottom: 3rem; }
.guide-meta { display:flex; gap: 1rem; align-items:center; font-size: 0.8125rem; color: var(--text-tertiary); margin-bottom: 0.75rem; }
.guide-lead { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--text-secondary); max-width: 65ch; line-height: 1.65; margin-top: 0.5rem; }
.guide-layout { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr; gap: 3rem; }
@media (min-width: 1024px) {
  .guide-layout { grid-template-columns: minmax(0, 8fr) minmax(0, 4fr); }
}
.guide-content h2 { margin-top: 2.5rem; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content p, .guide-content li { color: var(--text-secondary); line-height: 1.75; margin-bottom: 1rem; }
.guide-content ul { padding-left: 1.5rem; margin-bottom: 1.5rem; }
.important-warning { background: var(--color-surface-raised); border-left: 4px solid var(--color-accent-orange); padding: 1rem; border-radius: var(--radius-md); margin-top: 1rem; color: var(--text-secondary); }
.guide-sidebar { display:flex; flex-direction:column; gap: 1.5rem; }
.guide-sidebar .card { padding: 1.25rem; }
</style>
